69
00:04:03,860 --> 00:04:06,182
is one of the most challenging parts of game making.

70
00:04:07,263 --> 00:04:10,105
primarily because you have no revenue and you have high uncertainty.

71
00:04:10,305 --> 00:04:12,166
And as a product manager, you also have no data.

72
00:04:13,387 --> 00:04:17,569
So I would, you know, I guess an analogy that I frequently use is

73
00:04:17,589 --> 00:04:22,713
it's like being stuck in a long, dark tunnel where you're walking

74
00:04:22,733 --> 00:04:25,975
with a group of people and hoping that you've picked the right direction to walk in.

75
00:04:28,007 --> 00:04:31,529
So decisions in this stage have a large impact on the product.

76
00:04:32,150 --> 00:04:34,551
So this is why the first lesson that we learned

77
00:04:34,571 --> 00:04:37,393
at this first stage is the foundation setter.

78
00:04:37,594 --> 00:04:38,935
We were trying to answer the question,

79
00:04:39,575 --> 00:04:40,556
how can we start right?

80
00:04:42,185 --> 00:04:44,947
So development is risky business and in 2010,

81
00:04:45,947 --> 00:04:47,708
the good part about being on a new platform

82
00:04:48,229 --> 00:04:52,191
is that you are at the cusp of crazy growth.

83
00:04:52,732 --> 00:04:54,973
However, the other thing that's pretty bad about it

84
00:04:55,053 --> 00:04:59,156
is that you really don't have that many references

85
00:04:59,216 --> 00:05:00,116
of what good looks like.

86
00:05:00,156 --> 00:05:01,277
You kinda need to figure it out.

87
00:05:03,602 --> 00:05:05,284
In development, we ask lots of questions.

88
00:05:05,664 --> 00:05:06,985
Things like, where do we start?

89
00:05:07,325 --> 00:05:08,046
What do you build?

90
00:05:08,526 --> 00:05:09,627
What should the gameplay be?

91
00:05:09,868 --> 00:05:10,728
What should the meta be?

92
00:05:11,289 --> 00:05:13,471
How are we going to attain, retain, and monetize?

93
00:05:14,311 --> 00:05:15,853
And how can we make good decisions

94
00:05:15,913 --> 00:05:17,954
while lacking any data?

95
00:05:19,676 --> 00:05:22,038
So I suppose with some good fortune,

96
00:05:22,418 --> 00:05:24,100
the Sims FreePlay team was able to leverage

97
00:05:24,140 --> 00:05:26,762
some of its existing strengths and manage some risk.

98
00:05:27,861 --> 00:05:31,364
So as mentioned previously, FireMonkeys has a long,

99
00:05:31,865 --> 00:05:35,248
a pretty strong legacy of building mobile titles

100
00:05:35,308 --> 00:05:36,909
even before smartphones were around.

101
00:05:38,231 --> 00:05:40,232
There was a similar team that had previously shipped

102
00:05:40,333 --> 00:05:43,315
premium Sims titles, so they were familiar with each other

103
00:05:43,415 --> 00:05:45,117
and also familiar with the brand on mobile.

104
00:05:45,798 --> 00:05:48,000
So that was how we leveraged some of our strengths.

105
00:05:50,417 --> 00:05:51,737
A key unknown was free-to-play.

106
00:05:53,078 --> 00:05:55,020
The studio had no experience doing free-to-play.

107
00:05:55,140 --> 00:05:56,761
We were one of the first free-to-play titles

108
00:05:56,801 --> 00:05:58,202
that were launched by EA Mobile.

109
00:05:59,963 --> 00:06:03,605
And we didn't quite know how do you turn a sandbox simulation

110
00:06:03,645 --> 00:06:04,606
game to be free-to-play.

111
00:06:06,391 --> 00:06:07,712
So how do we mitigate unknowns?

112
00:06:07,772 --> 00:06:09,873
Well, you honestly make some guesses

113
00:06:09,953 --> 00:06:11,894
and just try to use your best judgment

114
00:06:12,294 --> 00:06:14,875
of studying some successful competitors in the market,

115
00:06:15,015 --> 00:06:18,817
of which clearly there was some in social Facebook space.

116
00:06:20,558 --> 00:06:23,740
And I guess again, good fortune was that

117
00:06:24,780 --> 00:06:26,261
the development was time box.

118
00:06:26,381 --> 00:06:28,541
Because historically, at least at that point,

119
00:06:28,561 --> 00:06:30,842
with premium mobile titles, we really

120
00:06:30,862 --> 00:06:32,162
needed to ship them quite quickly.

121
00:06:32,202 --> 00:06:33,843
And you really couldn't take your own sweet time.

122
00:06:34,223 --> 00:06:37,023
So that meant that while you were taking risks,

123
00:06:37,243 --> 00:06:39,164
you were forced to make decisions and just get it out.

124
00:06:44,665 --> 00:06:45,985
So these are some of the foundations

125
00:06:46,005 --> 00:06:46,946
that we ended up picking.

126
00:06:47,686 --> 00:06:49,886
Just so if you're not aware of how the game works,

127
00:06:49,926 --> 00:06:53,067
this is kind of like the core loop and the broad meta.

128
00:06:55,065 --> 00:06:58,450
So players have sims who they just give them appointments.

129
00:06:58,510 --> 00:07:01,434
For instance, in this case, we're asking sim to do a movie marathon.

130
00:07:02,376 --> 00:07:03,958
Set up the appointment. It takes time.

131
00:07:04,479 --> 00:07:09,226
And then in exchange, once it's done, you collect simoleons and XP, XP that.

132
00:07:09,667 --> 00:07:13,531
you know, this gives you progression in your player level. And simoleons you can spend in

133
00:07:13,731 --> 00:07:18,095
something like the build mode store where you have small amounts of spend and then you go into

134
00:07:18,115 --> 00:07:23,200
the town map which is a higher level where you can spend on building more houses and community

135
00:07:23,240 --> 00:07:29,446
lots which lets you expand your sim town. So these were the foundations that we kind of set the game

136
00:07:29,526 --> 00:07:29,746
upon.

137
00:07:31,802 --> 00:07:34,844
And so to summarize, the foundation setter,

138
00:07:35,024 --> 00:07:36,605
well, first thing is you need to be honest,

139
00:07:36,945 --> 00:07:38,986
leverage what you do know, and mitigate what you don't.

140
00:07:39,927 --> 00:07:41,748
Generally, try to resist the temptation

141
00:07:41,788 --> 00:07:43,669
to innovate on everything, because if you do,

142
00:07:44,670 --> 00:07:47,752
there's too many ways that things can go wrong.

143
00:07:49,513 --> 00:07:52,115
And lastly, there's no recipe for success, right?

144
00:07:52,495 --> 00:07:55,537
Like there's no kind of fixed thing that you can do

145
00:07:55,557 --> 00:07:57,458
where you guarantee any sort of success,

146
00:07:57,498 --> 00:07:59,840
you just need to exercise your best judgment.

147
00:08:03,692 --> 00:08:05,234
So for development, we're going to launch.

148
00:08:06,075 --> 00:08:08,517
In launch, quite usually, you know,

149
00:08:08,557 --> 00:08:10,819
hopefully you're lucky enough that you get high installs

150
00:08:10,999 --> 00:08:12,661
and then with high installs, your revenue spikes.

151
00:08:13,221 --> 00:08:14,542
Your return is normally not that great

152
00:08:14,663 --> 00:08:17,846
because perhaps your team is quite large at that point

153
00:08:18,266 --> 00:08:20,008
or maybe you haven't quite figured out

154
00:08:20,048 --> 00:08:23,531
how do you actually drive your key KPIs.

155
00:08:24,352 --> 00:08:24,992
So in stage two,

156
00:08:26,497 --> 00:08:28,377
It's the puzzle solver, where we really

157
00:08:28,397 --> 00:08:30,438
try to solve the puzzle of live service,

158
00:08:30,679 --> 00:08:32,880
answering the question of, how can we set the game up

159
00:08:32,940 --> 00:08:34,160
for long-term success?

160
00:08:37,522 --> 00:08:42,964
So to use Sims Replay as an example, at launch,

161
00:08:43,604 --> 00:08:46,026
this is what a DAU roughly mapped at.

162
00:08:47,366 --> 00:08:49,987
The Sims is an extremely strong brand and well-loved.

163
00:08:50,488 --> 00:08:53,289
So it naturally came with really strong installs.

164
00:08:54,601 --> 00:08:56,542
However, you can see our DAU started to slide,

165
00:08:57,463 --> 00:08:59,744
and it seems like our initial life service plan

166
00:08:59,764 --> 00:09:00,664
wasn't quite working out.

167
00:09:03,006 --> 00:09:03,786
So what was wrong?

168
00:09:04,667 --> 00:09:06,548
So I think to answer that question,

169
00:09:06,568 --> 00:09:09,169
we firstly need to understand what life service actually is.

170
00:09:10,150 --> 00:09:12,131
And the way I understand life service,

171
00:09:12,471 --> 00:09:16,213
it's like a puzzle which you have to kind of do

172
00:09:16,453 --> 00:09:17,774
under time pressure.

173
00:09:20,008 --> 00:09:21,630
There's a couple of elements that you're working with.

174
00:09:21,990 --> 00:09:25,252
That includes dev time, your spending development time

175
00:09:25,292 --> 00:09:28,634
to get some sort of output, of which the output then

176
00:09:28,734 --> 00:09:31,376
drives some of your numbers, like your installs, retention,

177
00:09:31,416 --> 00:09:31,856
and revenue.

178
00:09:33,297 --> 00:09:35,979
So how best you solve this puzzle

179
00:09:36,720 --> 00:09:38,081
will determine your success.

180
00:09:39,782 --> 00:09:41,002
Problem is that development time can

181
00:09:41,022 --> 00:09:42,584
be spent on multiple different things,

182
00:09:42,744 --> 00:09:45,766
like maintenance, events, content, new features,

183
00:09:45,786 --> 00:09:46,866
a whole heap of other things.

184
00:09:48,769 --> 00:09:49,950
And it's how you find that balance

185
00:09:50,010 --> 00:09:51,491
of managing the input and output

186
00:09:51,892 --> 00:09:54,114
that effectively lets you get the best results

187
00:09:54,194 --> 00:09:55,916
in order to try to achieve some growth.

188
00:09:59,120 --> 00:10:02,023
So different games will definitely face

189
00:10:02,063 --> 00:10:03,104
different problems at launch.

190
00:10:03,684 --> 00:10:05,166
And in some free play, the first thing you had to do

191
00:10:05,226 --> 00:10:07,288
is really try to identify what was wrong.

192
00:10:09,208 --> 00:10:14,711
So through updates, our live service plan was basically to put content directly into the Buildmode store.

193
00:10:15,271 --> 00:10:23,835
Remember, again, this is more than seven years ago, and there really wasn't a lot of competitor games that could give us some guidance.

194
00:10:25,085 --> 00:10:27,046
So put the content in the store, and then we saw the

195
00:10:27,066 --> 00:10:28,848
numbers, or our DAU saw the slide.

196
00:10:29,848 --> 00:10:33,231
And the reality is that just putting things directly into

197
00:10:33,271 --> 00:10:36,053
the store really doesn't quite sustain DAU, because players

198
00:10:36,073 --> 00:10:37,835
can just consume the content immediately.

199
00:10:38,175 --> 00:10:39,576
If I want that so far, I would just buy it.

200
00:10:39,856 --> 00:10:43,399
I don't really need to wait four weeks to buy it.

201
00:10:45,420 --> 00:10:48,443
And the problem was that the way we were delivering content

202
00:10:48,483 --> 00:10:50,224
was not giving us the return that we needed.

203
00:10:50,444 --> 00:10:52,826
So we needed to really find a way to

204
00:10:52,866 --> 00:10:54,147
retain players for longer.

205
00:10:56,168 --> 00:10:57,449
So how do we solve this problem?

206
00:10:57,910 --> 00:10:59,711
We knew that, yes, the problem was the way

207
00:11:00,031 --> 00:11:01,051
we were delivering content,

208
00:11:01,472 --> 00:11:03,553
so we figured a different way of delivering it.

209
00:11:04,033 --> 00:11:06,415
So one thing that the team experimented with

210
00:11:06,495 --> 00:11:07,835
was the notion of quests.

211
00:11:08,436 --> 00:11:10,757
We started putting content behind quests,

212
00:11:11,458 --> 00:11:13,339
where players had to engage in a quest

213
00:11:13,399 --> 00:11:15,020
in order to win content at the end.

214
00:11:16,100 --> 00:11:18,262
And how it works is really quite simple.

215
00:11:19,282 --> 00:11:19,963
The update drops.

216
00:11:21,393 --> 00:11:24,294
Players have to go through a quest for 5 to 14 days,

217
00:11:24,454 --> 00:11:26,095
actually engaging and sticking around.

218
00:11:26,655 --> 00:11:28,356
And then if they're successful, they

219
00:11:28,376 --> 00:11:29,956
get to win the content as we want.

220
00:11:31,097 --> 00:11:34,598
So this is some UI showing both the timer, the prize,

221
00:11:34,678 --> 00:11:36,879
as well as progression, as well as story

222
00:11:37,079 --> 00:11:39,199
that we have to write for the quest.

223
00:11:40,560 --> 00:11:43,981
So it worked well in extending the content lifespan

224
00:11:44,041 --> 00:11:45,261
and helped to solve the puzzle.

225
00:11:46,642 --> 00:11:50,205
And so as a result, we started seeing numbers start moving

226
00:11:50,345 --> 00:11:54,388
slowly upwards as we started introducing Quests more and

227
00:11:54,408 --> 00:11:55,189
more in our updates.

228
00:11:57,811 --> 00:11:59,713
And DAU gradually started to grow.

229
00:12:00,934 --> 00:12:06,639
So to summarize, lesson two is a puzzle solver, where the

230
00:12:06,659 --> 00:12:09,681
first thing you have to do is identify the key problems at

231
00:12:09,741 --> 00:12:13,845
launch, and then solve, use live services, and solve that

232
00:12:13,885 --> 00:12:14,906
puzzle of live services.

233
00:12:16,857 --> 00:12:19,119
And solving the puzzle is actually really key to actually

234
00:12:19,159 --> 00:12:20,179
having a viable product.

235
00:12:20,299 --> 00:12:21,900
If not, all your numbers start dropping,

236
00:12:22,081 --> 00:12:24,762
and it really doesn't make sense to continue, really

237
00:12:24,802 --> 00:12:27,284
continue running live service.

238
00:12:33,888 --> 00:12:38,391
So after launch, we go into this is probably the best stage,

239
00:12:38,411 --> 00:12:40,352
because it's where you feel kind of invincible.

240
00:12:40,552 --> 00:12:42,053
But it really is the growth stage.

241
00:12:43,175 --> 00:12:47,497
where revenue starts to increase, you can start reducing your costs and your return

242
00:12:47,517 --> 00:12:53,339
actually increases. It's worth noting that, of course, if you take too long to actually

243
00:12:53,379 --> 00:12:57,461
invest in growth, and if you don't realize that you're actually, you've solved the puzzle

244
00:12:57,481 --> 00:13:01,142
and you're not, and you're kind of moving to the growth stage, you will be missing out

245
00:13:01,182 --> 00:13:06,524
on a chance to really quickly, you know, kickstart, you know, some of the growth of some of your

246
00:13:06,544 --> 00:13:10,626
numbers. So lesson three is the growth investor.

247
00:13:12,370 --> 00:13:14,470
Where we try to answer the question here,

248
00:13:14,630 --> 00:13:15,951
which is how can we scale?

249
00:13:16,091 --> 00:13:18,091
If you've solved the puzzle, you know what works,

250
00:13:18,391 --> 00:13:19,152
how do you scale?

251
00:13:20,952 --> 00:13:23,033
So the Sims FreePlay is a simulation sandbox game.

