And as explained previously with the quests,

253
00:13:28,674 --> 00:13:33,336
we work best, we basically know how to drive our numbers

254
00:13:33,436 --> 00:13:36,076
provided that we know how to use content.

255
00:13:37,276 --> 00:13:40,417
And given that we've solved the puzzle of delivering content,

256
00:13:40,877 --> 00:13:43,118
now what we need to do is just increase.

257
00:13:43,278 --> 00:13:45,318
One thing we need to do to scale is to increase content

258
00:13:45,338 --> 00:13:45,819
production.

259
00:13:47,119 --> 00:13:49,400
First thing we did was grow the internal art team.

260
00:13:49,780 --> 00:13:51,580
Now we know where if we build more assets,

261
00:13:52,581 --> 00:13:53,721
you can drive more KPIs.

262
00:13:55,122 --> 00:13:57,042
The benefit about growing the internal art team as well is

263
00:13:57,082 --> 00:14:00,243
that it allows us to work more on outsourcing as well, which

264
00:14:00,363 --> 00:14:02,344
multiplies the amount of content that you

265
00:14:02,364 --> 00:14:03,204
can put into your game.

266
00:14:04,547 --> 00:14:07,209
As a result, over the past seven years with every update,

267
00:14:07,249 --> 00:14:11,031
we've been steadily adding assets with every update.

268
00:14:11,211 --> 00:14:14,072
Some numbers include like we have more than 6,000

269
00:14:14,353 --> 00:14:16,954
built-in objects and more than 11,000 customization

270
00:14:16,974 --> 00:14:18,155
and coding options.

271
00:14:22,644 --> 00:14:25,766
For a simulation sandbox game, this actually

272
00:14:25,806 --> 00:14:29,289
has the added benefit of making it really hard for new titles

273
00:14:29,329 --> 00:14:29,909
to compete.

274
00:14:30,189 --> 00:14:32,131
And if you have any sense of how the market is,

275
00:14:32,891 --> 00:14:35,533
a lot of the titles that still continue

276
00:14:35,553 --> 00:14:37,215
to be in the top grossing actually

277
00:14:37,235 --> 00:14:39,036
tend to be quite old, because they actually

278
00:14:39,356 --> 00:14:40,577
get stronger over time.

279
00:14:41,878 --> 00:14:45,301
By virtue of the fact that if it's a simulation sandbox,

280
00:14:45,461 --> 00:14:46,682
the more options they give players,

281
00:14:46,702 --> 00:14:48,904
the more likely they are going to just stick with the game,

282
00:14:48,924 --> 00:14:50,525
because it allows them to tell more stories

283
00:14:50,605 --> 00:14:51,686
and just do a lot more.

284
00:14:53,110 --> 00:14:58,157
So the next thing that we did to try to scale and grow,

285
00:14:58,778 --> 00:15:01,101
invest in growth, was to reduce costs.

286
00:15:02,763 --> 00:15:04,706
So we reduced costs through tools.

287
00:15:06,023 --> 00:15:08,325
Tools help to reduce engineering time, which is

288
00:15:08,385 --> 00:15:11,847
highly valuable, and really shouldn't be spent on

289
00:15:11,887 --> 00:15:13,449
repetitive things like live events.

290
00:15:14,870 --> 00:15:16,671
Engineering time could be better spent building

291
00:15:16,711 --> 00:15:17,111
features.

292
00:15:17,972 --> 00:15:20,514
And the other thing that tools gave us was the opportunity to

293
00:15:20,574 --> 00:15:21,835
empower other disciplines.

294
00:15:22,556 --> 00:15:24,817
Like for instance, we have the data tool for tuning where

295
00:15:26,439 --> 00:15:30,382
designers can just put in tuning without

296
00:15:30,422 --> 00:15:31,202
needing an engineer.

297
00:15:32,225 --> 00:15:35,487
Same way with quests, when we knew that quests were working,

298
00:15:35,527 --> 00:15:37,389
we started to create templates for quests

299
00:15:37,589 --> 00:15:41,331
so that it was just, in general, there was less room for error.

300
00:15:41,511 --> 00:15:45,493
And then design could put things in with minimal code effort.

301
00:15:46,554 --> 00:15:49,796
We built sales tools so that PMs could create sales and rerun

302
00:15:49,816 --> 00:15:51,637
sales easily without needing any code.

303
00:15:51,837 --> 00:15:54,039
And we also built a scheduler tool

304
00:15:54,219 --> 00:15:56,380
so that if we, in the event that we

305
00:15:56,400 --> 00:15:59,982
needed to move our events around or just push in new events,

306
00:16:00,022 --> 00:16:00,523
we could do it.

307
00:16:01,163 --> 00:16:02,184
extremely quickly.

308
00:16:05,266 --> 00:16:09,488
Another thing worth noting is that definitely there are economies of scale where the more we

309
00:16:09,508 --> 00:16:16,053
do something the better that we will get at it. So the third thing that we did to invest in growth

310
00:16:16,273 --> 00:16:20,816
was to actually look at the features themselves. So we knew that quests work, however of course

311
00:16:21,236 --> 00:16:26,700
once the quest ended you would see your numbers drop again. So what we figured was we should just

312
00:16:27,120 --> 00:16:28,421
chain all the quests together.

313
00:16:30,091 --> 00:16:39,234
Where here you can see examples of the different quests that unlock at different levels, like cooking on the spin plant, or horses for instance.

314
00:16:40,872 --> 00:16:43,435
And for simulation sandbox game, this is quite interesting

315
00:16:43,515 --> 00:16:47,580
because it gave players a path to progress,

316
00:16:47,620 --> 00:16:48,801
where they could unlock features,

317
00:16:50,463 --> 00:16:53,646
where if not everyone is extremely creative

318
00:16:53,827 --> 00:16:55,889
and not everyone knows how to set goals

319
00:16:55,929 --> 00:16:58,993
in a sandbox space, but now with this sort of progression

320
00:16:59,013 --> 00:17:00,935
that we're able to offer players where

321
00:17:01,635 --> 00:17:05,158
as they level up they get an opportunity to play through quests that unlock new features which

322
00:17:05,178 --> 00:17:11,082
makes them feel like they are really kind of growing and expanding the possibility of what

323
00:17:11,122 --> 00:17:16,166
they can do in the game. So this helped to strengthen our baselines in general and to

324
00:17:16,206 --> 00:17:23,631
give players something to do in between updates and in between events. So the fourth thing that we did to

325
00:17:26,780 --> 00:17:31,566
investing growth was this really cool thing where we started looking at user-generated content.

326
00:17:34,816 --> 00:17:38,459
So houses are actually very expensive for us to build.

327
00:17:38,479 --> 00:17:41,842
It takes an artist probably several days

328
00:17:42,903 --> 00:17:43,864
just to put a house together.

329
00:17:43,884 --> 00:17:46,586
And this is just using our assets that exist.

330
00:17:46,606 --> 00:17:50,509
However, it's highly demanded and valued by players.

331
00:17:50,930 --> 00:17:53,772
As you saw briefly previously, there was a town map.

332
00:17:53,832 --> 00:17:55,514
And players actually set goals on,

333
00:17:55,654 --> 00:17:58,156
I want to put all these amazing mansions on my town map.

334
00:17:58,536 --> 00:18:00,338
But real problem was that we just could not

335
00:18:00,398 --> 00:18:01,138
afford to build them.

336
00:18:02,960 --> 00:18:05,001
So we built this feature, which is

337
00:18:05,041 --> 00:18:06,462
one of our most successful features,

338
00:18:07,002 --> 00:18:09,483
called the Architect Homes, which allows players

339
00:18:09,503 --> 00:18:10,743
to submit their houses.

340
00:18:11,504 --> 00:18:14,785
And we actually pick them manually every two weeks.

341
00:18:15,325 --> 00:18:18,506
And we data push them out to players,

342
00:18:19,027 --> 00:18:20,707
allowing them to both preview and purchase.

343
00:18:20,727 --> 00:18:24,949
I would say that this feature has been around for years.

344
00:18:25,269 --> 00:18:28,290
And more than 80% of our houses are actually

345
00:18:28,690 --> 00:18:29,671
user-generated houses.

346
00:18:31,382 --> 00:18:33,263
Effectively, this removes us completely.

347
00:18:33,283 --> 00:18:35,565
With the exception of picking, it removes us completely

348
00:18:35,605 --> 00:18:36,745
as a bottleneck for content.

349
00:18:37,506 --> 00:18:40,367
And it allows players to showcase what they've built.

350
00:18:40,567 --> 00:18:44,209
And to a large extent, the things that they build

351
00:18:44,249 --> 00:18:45,790
are way better than anything that we could build.

352
00:18:49,012 --> 00:18:52,314
So to summarize, lesson three, in the growth stage.

353
00:18:53,930 --> 00:18:55,731
What you really want to do is invest in growth.

354
00:18:56,611 --> 00:18:57,712
Invest in the thing that works,

355
00:18:58,092 --> 00:18:59,712
and clearly as explained,

356
00:18:59,732 --> 00:19:01,713
there are multiple ways of investing in growth.

357
00:19:03,153 --> 00:19:04,794
You can gain efficiencies in content creation

358
00:19:04,854 --> 00:19:06,555
and consumption, that's basically the goal.

359
00:19:07,535 --> 00:19:10,136
And if you don't know much about simulation games,

360
00:19:10,196 --> 00:19:12,217
really, they actually do get stronger over time.

361
00:19:14,897 --> 00:19:16,898
And the opportunity cost if you can't scale,

362
00:19:16,918 --> 00:19:18,239
there's definitely opportunity cost

363
00:19:18,279 --> 00:19:21,220
if you're not trying to scale when the time is right.

364
00:19:27,024 --> 00:19:28,986
So the paradox of content.

365
00:19:29,486 --> 00:19:31,828
Well, it's easy to say, let's build a pipeline.

366
00:19:32,028 --> 00:19:33,350
Let's just, we know content works,

367
00:19:33,370 --> 00:19:34,731
let's just build lots of content, right?

368
00:19:35,711 --> 00:19:37,053
So we know that we need to build content.

369
00:19:37,713 --> 00:19:38,774
We know how to build it.

370
00:19:40,435 --> 00:19:41,937
The real problem is what should we build?

371
00:19:44,779 --> 00:19:47,461
So this Afro guy says that if you build it, they will come.

372
00:19:49,334 --> 00:19:51,075
But reality is no, that's not true.

373
00:19:51,835 --> 00:19:54,437
And we learned that the hard way by building things

374
00:19:54,497 --> 00:19:56,237
that players just didn't want.

375
00:19:57,698 --> 00:20:01,220
And the difference between a good content that people want

376
00:20:01,400 --> 00:20:04,341
and a dark content can be more than 50%.

377
00:20:04,902 --> 00:20:06,422
An example that comes to mind is

378
00:20:07,443 --> 00:20:13,365
Christmas events tend to be our biggest and most expensive events because it's great seasonality.

379
00:20:13,945 --> 00:20:18,747
So there was one Christmas where we decided to go fantasy. We were like, oh fantasy, you know, it would be quite cool.

380
00:20:19,547 --> 00:20:23,849
The update dropped, the event started, and then on Facebook people started asking

381
00:20:24,849 --> 00:20:25,769
where's the Christmas event?

382
00:20:26,990 --> 00:20:33,572
So there's a really painful lesson because players, you know, if they're not really into it, they're just not going to actually play it.

383
00:20:35,073 --> 00:20:36,773
So lesson four is the keen listener.

384
00:20:38,832 --> 00:20:40,915
And really we're trying to answer the question here

385
00:20:41,275 --> 00:20:43,098
of what should we build?

386
00:20:47,244 --> 00:20:50,810
And surprise, well, at least for the Sims,

387
00:20:50,870 --> 00:20:53,013
we have great audience, so the players will tell you.

388
00:20:54,444 --> 00:20:56,547
Since we play an audience, SKU is younger.

389
00:20:57,227 --> 00:20:59,590
They're highly vocal with lots of opinions.

390
00:21:00,491 --> 00:21:02,413
And the challenge, or the thing that we have to do,

391
00:21:02,533 --> 00:21:04,856
is actually just manage those channels.

392
00:21:05,577 --> 00:21:08,079
So we use channels like Facebook, Twitter,

393
00:21:08,580 --> 00:21:10,282
EA runs this thing called Game Changers

394
00:21:10,362 --> 00:21:11,603
with our community managers.

395
00:21:12,324 --> 00:21:16,726
We have forums, websites, and customer support, as well as internal channels where we actually

396
00:21:16,886 --> 00:21:22,388
ask questions like customer satisfaction surveys, user experience research. These are all the

397
00:21:22,408 --> 00:21:27,010
different things that we do in order to get a sense of what should we build, what do players

398
00:21:27,070 --> 00:21:27,570
actually want.

399
00:21:28,984 --> 00:21:30,625
Some of the things that we can learn include

400
00:21:31,285 --> 00:21:32,305
what content do they want?

401
00:21:32,925 --> 00:21:35,066
When it comes to surveys, we actually brainstorm

402
00:21:35,086 --> 00:21:39,187
a list of things like, do they want Venetian mansions?

403
00:21:39,588 --> 00:21:42,729
Or do they want submarines?

404
00:21:42,909 --> 00:21:43,949
Or do they wanna be in space?

405
00:21:43,989 --> 00:21:45,930
We actually force them to stack rank it.

406
00:21:46,290 --> 00:21:49,591
And that is how we use to prioritize our content roadmap.

407
00:21:51,712 --> 00:21:53,912
We ask them things like, what would you like to see again?

408
00:21:54,112 --> 00:21:55,633
And that's something that we also use

409
00:21:55,693 --> 00:21:58,594
to plan our calendar of reruns.

410
00:21:59,910 --> 00:22:01,611
This is something that we can tell actually

411
00:22:01,671 --> 00:22:03,712
through telemetry, but because we have different sources

412
00:22:03,732 --> 00:22:06,154
of information, triangulating that is normally

413
00:22:06,174 --> 00:22:06,754
quite a good thing.

414
00:22:09,456 --> 00:22:11,477
Sometimes you also come up with hypotheses

415
00:22:11,557 --> 00:22:13,379
of what some features might be,

416
00:22:13,699 --> 00:22:15,760
like for instance, professions or pregnancy.

417
00:22:16,921 --> 00:22:18,902
These were all things that we had hypothesized

418
00:22:18,942 --> 00:22:22,324
and then we put into a survey and then figured

419
00:22:22,464 --> 00:22:24,226
which ones would actually work the best,

420
00:22:24,286 --> 00:22:26,507
so which ones were actually most highly desired.

421
00:22:28,330 --> 00:22:31,012
And also understanding how the players feel about the features that we release.

422
00:22:31,072 --> 00:22:33,973
For instance, you know, how many people are actually using the relationship system?

423
00:22:34,013 --> 00:22:35,194
How important is it for them?

424
00:22:35,734 --> 00:22:38,215
And trying to get a sense of should we actually iterate?

425
00:22:38,235 --> 00:22:40,476
Should we spend any time optimizing this system?

426
00:22:42,309 --> 00:22:47,171
Lastly, it's hard, but sometimes it is possible to try to understand some of their motivations,

427
00:22:47,211 --> 00:22:49,693
the kind of why, why do they actually want this thing.

428
00:22:50,793 --> 00:22:55,535
It's challenging given that we are a simulation sandbox and different people have different

429
00:22:55,595 --> 00:22:58,337
goals and different reasons for wanting certain things.

430
00:22:59,937 --> 00:23:05,600
But most recently we had done a customer satisfaction survey that kind of clarified something that

431
00:23:05,820 --> 00:23:09,202
gave us insight to something that we never thought of, actually.

432
00:23:10,042 --> 00:23:10,222
So...

433
00:23:12,224 --> 00:23:15,066
Hair is something that does very well in our game.

434
00:23:16,187 --> 00:23:17,748
It's been doing very well for years.

435
00:23:17,768 --> 00:23:20,009
It's something that players have always been,

436
00:23:20,089 --> 00:23:21,210
just an example of hair,

437
00:23:22,051 --> 00:23:25,933
players have been asking on all channels for years,

438
00:23:26,053 --> 00:23:27,334
and we've always, you know,

439
00:23:27,354 --> 00:23:29,435
we've started running like a hair hobby event,

440
00:23:29,475 --> 00:23:32,197
and we've since added more hair hobby events

441
00:23:32,337 --> 00:23:33,718
and more hair live events.

442
00:23:36,160 --> 00:23:39,343
Our understanding of why players wanted hair was basically,

443
00:23:39,783 --> 00:23:42,525
we just thought that they look just like customization

444
00:23:42,845 --> 00:23:44,106
and hair is just cool.

445
00:23:44,246 --> 00:23:48,870
And another thought that we had was that hair is actually,

446
00:23:50,971 --> 00:23:53,053
some, you know, hair means more

447
00:23:53,113 --> 00:23:56,195
because our hair that we had launched initially

448
00:23:56,215 --> 00:23:58,197
with the game didn't look very good.

449
00:23:58,257 --> 00:24:00,258
So as such, players actually wanted more hair.

450
00:24:02,398 --> 00:24:06,419
So in the customer satisfaction survey that we had run recently, we asked,

451
00:24:06,779 --> 00:24:11,560
why did you really enjoy this recent boutique hair life event?

452
00:24:12,340 --> 00:24:15,201
And it gave us some insight that we never,

453
00:24:15,681 --> 00:24:18,421
it kind of gave us insight that we had never thought of,

454
00:24:18,501 --> 00:24:21,422
at least in the development team who have been building hair for years.

455
00:24:21,462 --> 00:24:23,282
You know, we didn't actually realize this.

456
00:24:24,202 --> 00:24:25,623
So the insight was...

457
00:24:27,144 --> 00:24:33,148
Look at this. This is our sim tracker. The sim tracker is something that we use for, that players use to

458
00:24:33,629 --> 00:24:37,832
select between their sims because players have lots of sims. Some players have 30 plus sims.

459
00:24:39,333 --> 00:24:41,155
And if we look a bit closer,

460
00:24:41,175 --> 00:24:45,098
you can notice something.

461
00:24:53,564 --> 00:24:53,865
So,

462
00:24:54,865 --> 00:24:56,226
players actually want hair.

463
00:24:57,610 --> 00:24:59,326
because sims have the same face.

464
00:25:01,509 --> 00:25:04,049
And hair is actually, you know,

465
00:25:04,710 --> 00:25:06,430
cheaper for us to create than face.

466
00:25:07,530 --> 00:25:10,411
But this was insight that we actually didn't realize

467
00:25:10,491 --> 00:25:12,932
because of us, the sim track is actually really small

468
00:25:13,312 --> 00:25:15,853
and, you know, the tiny little thumbnail of sims

469
00:25:15,953 --> 00:25:18,434
meant that players of, or same face sims

470
00:25:18,594 --> 00:25:20,575
meant that players actually couldn't tell them apart.

471
00:25:21,055 --> 00:25:22,715
So with more hair options,

472
00:25:22,815 --> 00:25:25,856
they now had more ways of solving that problem

473
00:25:25,956 --> 00:25:27,737
in ways that we didn't ever think of.

474
00:25:28,797 --> 00:25:32,360
So that's one of the things that you get to learn and I think it's pretty cool to learn that

475
00:25:32,680 --> 00:25:40,646
years after we've been beating the drum of hair is great because players just like hair. Turns out there's actual utility in hair for our players.

476
00:25:43,408 --> 00:25:46,029
So to summarize, lesson four, the keen listener.

477
00:25:48,211 --> 00:25:54,215
So we earn our target audience, that's pretty clear since we play as SKUs young and SKUs female.

478
00:25:56,149 --> 00:25:59,152
We have to build multiple channels to both listen and ask questions

479
00:26:00,053 --> 00:26:03,497
because of how much it costs to develop content.

480
00:26:04,358 --> 00:26:07,321
This helps to guide development and guide the way we do things

481
00:26:07,361 --> 00:26:09,484
so it reduces risk of things not working out.

482
00:26:10,305 --> 00:26:13,128
And this is something that's really relevant all throughout the product lifecycle,

483
00:26:13,188 --> 00:26:15,731
although perhaps more relevant when you actually have a product out there.

484
00:26:20,087 --> 00:26:22,628
So we move on to stage four, after growth,

485
00:26:22,808 --> 00:26:24,129
which is the real fun part,

486
00:26:24,469 --> 00:26:25,870
you go into something called maturity.

487
00:26:26,690 --> 00:26:30,272
Here, your revenue kind of flattens,

488
00:26:30,372 --> 00:26:32,393
you can still continue to reduce costs,

489
00:26:32,653 --> 00:26:36,635
and your return is perhaps increasing but not as fast.

490
00:26:38,696 --> 00:26:42,297
Hopefully you hit maturity years into your life cycle,

491
00:26:42,337 --> 00:26:44,618
and not immediately, because that would be quite strange.

492
00:26:48,043 --> 00:26:53,585
Operating this long at a fixed pace of maybe six to eight weeks, you ship an update.

493
00:26:54,186 --> 00:26:56,226
It is fast, it's fast-paced.

494
00:26:56,707 --> 00:27:05,010
There's always going to be mistakes in live service, and so general issues that kind of snowball as you keep kicking the can down the road for many years.

495
00:27:05,891 --> 00:27:08,292
So lesson five is the fixer, which is

496
00:27:09,612 --> 00:27:10,553
how do we recover?

497
00:27:16,660 --> 00:27:21,021
So for mistakes in live service, there are several categories.

498
00:27:21,781 --> 00:27:23,862
The obvious ones are bugs, of which

499
00:27:23,902 --> 00:27:26,022
if you worked in a simulation game,

500
00:27:26,062 --> 00:27:27,623
they're always very hilarious bugs,

501
00:27:28,463 --> 00:27:30,223
things clipping each other and whatnot.

502
00:27:32,564 --> 00:27:34,345
As mentioned previously, there's

503
00:27:36,049 --> 00:27:37,609
Mistakes of not getting the content right,

504
00:27:37,690 --> 00:27:39,870
of which that's really hard to fix, right?

505
00:27:40,070 --> 00:27:44,111
Like if you invested lots of days building something

506
00:27:44,191 --> 00:27:46,772
and you kind of need to launch it effectively,

507
00:27:46,812 --> 00:27:48,993
and then you just probably won't launch it again.

508
00:27:52,133 --> 00:27:53,994
Next one is not getting the feature right, which

509
00:27:54,034 --> 00:27:57,055
is quite common, given that we, at least in 3Play,

510
00:27:57,075 --> 00:27:59,175
we don't really soft launch our features.

511
00:27:59,595 --> 00:28:00,756
We don't really have a way of testing

512
00:28:00,796 --> 00:28:02,616
whether it works or not, other than playing it

513
00:28:02,776 --> 00:28:03,937
before we launch it.

514
00:28:05,881 --> 00:28:08,262
These sorts of mistakes impact following, including stability,

515
00:28:08,882 --> 00:28:13,264
sentiment on social channels, and feature

516
00:28:13,324 --> 00:28:14,185
and event performance.

517
00:28:14,485 --> 00:28:19,467
So in general, you kind of need to decide how you deal with it.

518
00:28:19,487 --> 00:28:21,448
And like any good life service, you

519
00:28:21,468 --> 00:28:23,609
will need to have a triage process, which

520
00:28:23,649 --> 00:28:26,070
you kind of evaluate the severity, the impact,

521
00:28:26,270 --> 00:28:28,131
and kind of decide how urgent it is to fix.

522
00:28:29,580 --> 00:28:31,222
using the different channels that we mentioned previously,

523
00:28:31,242 --> 00:28:32,603
you have to communicate transparently

524
00:28:32,623 --> 00:28:35,787
and as well as obviously, I guess, timely.

525
00:28:37,609 --> 00:28:38,510
And with the other mistakes,

526
00:28:38,550 --> 00:28:40,512
you have to kind of try to find a way to deal with them

527
00:28:41,232 --> 00:28:45,077
based on the impact of what it's currently causing

528
00:28:45,577 --> 00:28:47,679
as well as the return of what it can get you,

529
00:28:47,760 --> 00:28:48,781
perhaps, if you solve it.

530
00:28:50,208 --> 00:28:52,151
You have to consider both the risks to player sentiment

531
00:28:52,191 --> 00:28:53,994
and KPIs, given that we are a live game.

532
00:28:54,254 --> 00:28:57,198
If you start changing things, players will notice

533
00:28:57,238 --> 00:28:58,199
and they will talk about it.

534
00:28:58,219 --> 00:29:00,282
So are you prepared for that?

535
00:29:01,925 --> 00:29:03,567
In general, rule of thumb is that if you are going

536
00:29:03,587 --> 00:29:05,389
to change something, it's easier to add something

537
00:29:05,409 --> 00:29:06,391
than it is to remove it.

538
00:29:12,007 --> 00:29:14,489
So another, this is not really a mistake,

539
00:29:14,529 --> 00:29:16,070
but it's just something that applies

540
00:29:16,170 --> 00:29:18,332
if you're running a long-term life service.

541
00:29:18,772 --> 00:29:20,514
It's the weakening foundations.

542
00:29:21,534 --> 00:29:22,615
These are some challenging things

543
00:29:22,655 --> 00:29:24,657
to overcome in a state of maturity.

544
00:29:26,445 --> 00:29:29,467
So one of the things that would happen is diminishing returns.

545
00:29:29,628 --> 00:29:31,589
If you keep doing the same thing over and over,

546
00:29:31,609 --> 00:29:33,070
an example would be SimCount.

547
00:29:33,590 --> 00:29:36,152
We give players SimCount if they level up

548
00:29:36,332 --> 00:29:38,574
so that they get to add more Sims to their SimTown,

549
00:29:38,614 --> 00:29:39,174
which is great.

550
00:29:40,915 --> 00:29:41,756
But like anything that.

551
00:29:42,336 --> 00:29:48,738
any reward, the first few times, maybe the first 10 sims is great, but by the 30th, 35th one,

552
00:29:48,898 --> 00:29:55,679
is it as valuable or do you still feel as much joy from getting it? Then they add a problem of

553
00:29:55,739 --> 00:30:02,541
course, scalability, like as previously seen, the sim tracker is going to keep, you know,

554
00:30:02,561 --> 00:30:05,282
you need a place where you have to keep scrolling through it.

555
00:30:08,238 --> 00:30:09,319
The next thing is expectation.

556
00:30:09,339 --> 00:30:11,261
So this is interesting because good design

557
00:30:11,301 --> 00:30:12,963
means that players know how to set expectations.

558
00:30:13,744 --> 00:30:15,725
However, it also would hamstring us

559
00:30:16,026 --> 00:30:18,048
because something like quests, for instance,

560
00:30:18,128 --> 00:30:19,489
is a fixed way of doing things.

561
00:30:19,569 --> 00:30:21,531
Players expect it to work in that same way.

562
00:30:21,651 --> 00:30:24,153
And even if we find ways, problems with it,

563
00:30:24,173 --> 00:30:25,214
or ways to optimize it.

564
00:30:26,284 --> 00:30:27,766
Players understand the rules, and they're not

565
00:30:27,826 --> 00:30:29,848
going to be super happy you start changing things

566
00:30:29,928 --> 00:30:30,329
around them.

567
00:30:30,349 --> 00:30:33,913
At the same time, they've also ritualized and figured out

568
00:30:34,033 --> 00:30:35,475
a solution of min-maxing it.

569
00:30:35,495 --> 00:30:37,878
So that's something that you need to take into account,

570
00:30:37,918 --> 00:30:41,702
knowing that the longer you run your live service,

571
00:30:41,802 --> 00:30:43,484
the more likely that players will have

572
00:30:43,544 --> 00:30:44,786
built up those expectations.

573
00:30:47,503 --> 00:30:48,384
The next is anchoring.

574
00:30:48,404 --> 00:30:53,889
On the PM side, you know, obviously if you anchor too low of a price,

575
00:30:54,309 --> 00:30:58,013
like what I mentioned previously, it's going to be quite hard for you to increase it, at least immediately.

576
00:30:59,632 --> 00:31:03,416
And when it comes to rewards, we tended to go really big

577
00:31:03,676 --> 00:31:06,599
with our whenever we launched a new event, where we went,

578
00:31:06,799 --> 00:31:10,322
like, here are heaps of rewards, and here are super high quality

579
00:31:10,402 --> 00:31:12,884
ones at the same time, only to realize that we can't actually

580
00:31:13,005 --> 00:31:14,005
keep up that pace.

581
00:31:15,387 --> 00:31:19,611
So that's quite hard, because in live service, players are like,

582
00:31:19,711 --> 00:31:21,472
but the other event was much stronger.

583
00:31:21,492 --> 00:31:22,814
I expected more.

584
00:31:23,414 --> 00:31:25,856
But yet, you kind of can't keep up that pace.

585
00:31:28,074 --> 00:31:29,455
So we have to be careful and thoughtful in how

586
00:31:29,495 --> 00:31:31,796
we solve these problems because it is,

587
00:31:33,017 --> 00:31:35,258
players have been used to something and you can't just,

588
00:31:35,318 --> 00:31:37,819
you know, it's not great to pull the rug from under them.

589
00:31:41,001 --> 00:31:43,282
So lesson five is immaturity.

590
00:31:43,302 --> 00:31:44,823
It's the fixer.

591
00:31:45,043 --> 00:31:47,184
It's normal and expected to trip up.

592
00:31:47,824 --> 00:31:49,465
Sometimes they're game-breaking things,

593
00:31:49,505 --> 00:31:50,566
so that's where you trip immediately,

594
00:31:50,586 --> 00:31:52,127
or there's weakening foundations

595
00:31:52,187 --> 00:31:55,088
where you do a slow motion fall, basically.

596
00:31:56,490 --> 00:32:00,513
You have to be prepared to fix bugs with an effective triage

597
00:32:00,553 --> 00:32:01,013
process.

598
00:32:03,355 --> 00:32:06,477
And regularly try to assess the fundamental problems

599
00:32:06,537 --> 00:32:09,759
in your games, because it keeps changing as the foundations

600
00:32:09,799 --> 00:32:10,980
weaken and things change.

601
00:32:11,661 --> 00:32:12,701
And consider solutions.

602
00:32:14,403 --> 00:32:17,205
This we found quite hard to do when

603
00:32:17,225 --> 00:32:19,726
you have been working on a title for so long.

604
00:32:19,786 --> 00:32:22,148
It's hard to take a step back and then evaluate what's

605
00:32:23,529 --> 00:32:26,190
Are we doing something wrong or actually what's happening?

606
00:32:26,210 --> 00:32:30,473
And we found that a good solution to this is actually to bring new people in.

607
00:32:30,493 --> 00:32:35,375
With a set of fresh eyes, we were able to find things like, you know, we were pricing certain

608
00:32:35,416 --> 00:32:40,178
things the exact same way because our engineering team was just duplicating the price and we forgot

609
00:32:40,198 --> 00:32:44,701
to actually price things. So these were all things that we uncovered when we brought new people in.

610
00:32:48,978 --> 00:32:51,199
And finally, be both careful and thoughtful

611
00:32:51,420 --> 00:32:52,801
with weakening foundations.

612
00:32:55,002 --> 00:32:58,064
So you can learn things clearly by making mistakes,

613
00:32:58,444 --> 00:33:01,306
but live service is primarily about launching and learning.

614
00:33:01,847 --> 00:33:04,829
So in six-week cycles, you learn by building,

615
00:33:04,869 --> 00:33:05,749
measuring, and learning.

616
00:33:07,090 --> 00:33:09,452
I look at every update as an opportunity

617
00:33:09,512 --> 00:33:11,333
to try new things and learn something.

618
00:33:11,353 --> 00:33:13,214
So I think that's a good approach to have.

619
00:33:14,474 --> 00:33:17,536
Two ways of testing hypotheses include launching and then measuring after,

620
00:33:17,556 --> 00:33:21,938
or of course, during A-B testing, or multivariate testing,

621
00:33:22,118 --> 00:33:24,819
where you are trying out different variables and seeing what works.

622
00:33:26,020 --> 00:33:30,842
For both, a very important principle applies, which is

623
00:33:31,463 --> 00:33:34,704
we have to set up your expectations and hypotheses in both instances

624
00:33:35,265 --> 00:33:36,525
before you actually do the thing.

625
00:33:36,885 --> 00:33:40,347
So this is one of the key ways in which you sharpen your judgment.

626
00:33:41,747 --> 00:33:45,950
My personal view is that it really doesn't matter if you're completely inaccurate of

627
00:33:45,990 --> 00:33:50,713
saying like, for instance, if we do this thing, the uplift might be 10 to 20% and then in

628
00:33:50,973 --> 00:33:51,834
reality it might be 40%.

629
00:33:51,954 --> 00:33:57,057
It doesn't matter because you took a stab at it and then, you know, it prevents you

630
00:33:57,077 --> 00:34:00,779
from falling into the trap of confirmation bias knowing like, yeah, I knew it would increase

631
00:34:00,860 --> 00:34:05,342
but you know, you said 10 to 20% so now you can adjust the way you're thinking to get

632
00:34:05,402 --> 00:34:09,605
closer to understanding how features perform in the future.

633
00:34:11,295 --> 00:34:14,357
So lesson six is the validated learner,

634
00:34:14,537 --> 00:34:17,199
which is how do we really make sure that we are learning

635
00:34:17,359 --> 00:34:19,180
and not just trying a bunch of things?

636
00:34:27,166 --> 00:34:28,246
So with A-B testing,

637
00:34:29,847 --> 00:34:31,608
general principle is to try to test changes

638
00:34:31,628 --> 00:34:33,109
where you're not certain on the impact.

639
00:34:34,250 --> 00:34:36,231
If you really know that it's gonna do something,

640
00:34:36,992 --> 00:34:38,773
unless you're trying to optimize it further,

641
00:34:38,793 --> 00:34:39,974
there's really no need to test it.

642
00:34:41,863 --> 00:34:46,567
A couple of things that we have done include optimizing the first-time user experience,

643
00:34:46,927 --> 00:34:50,950
where if you know anything about simulation titles, it's that there are heaps to teach

644
00:34:51,070 --> 00:34:53,652
players, and we wanted to reduce the number of steps.

645
00:34:55,592 --> 00:34:57,714
The real problem here with Sims FreePlay, I believe,

646
00:34:57,734 --> 00:35:00,956
was that creating another first-time user experience

647
00:35:01,237 --> 00:35:03,138
was a really expensive task.

648
00:35:03,739 --> 00:35:05,020
So that's the problem of A-B testing.

649
00:35:05,040 --> 00:35:06,181
If you're going to test something that you've already

650
00:35:06,201 --> 00:35:09,924
spent so much time on, you are much more likely to just go

651
00:35:09,944 --> 00:35:11,625
with the thing that you spent time on anyway.

652
00:35:12,586 --> 00:35:18,330
Fortunately, I believe in this instance, the test cohort was

653
00:35:18,410 --> 00:35:19,851
the winner, but only marginally.

654
00:35:21,728 --> 00:35:23,969
The next thing that we wanted to test was quest progression.

655
00:35:24,829 --> 00:35:27,970
So after five, six years of adding content,

656
00:35:28,791 --> 00:35:31,232
we actually found that we had the problem

657
00:35:31,252 --> 00:35:32,772
of having too much content.

658
00:35:33,012 --> 00:35:35,753
And players were actually not getting to the content.

659
00:35:36,073 --> 00:35:38,054
They were leaving before they saw the cool things.

660
00:35:38,754 --> 00:35:41,815
So we figured, OK, maybe let's shake it up.

661
00:35:41,855 --> 00:35:44,436
Let's try to get players to the content sooner.

662
00:35:44,596 --> 00:35:47,337
And we wanted to shorten the length of time

663
00:35:47,397 --> 00:35:48,677
it took to go through the quest.

664
00:35:50,928 --> 00:35:52,649
So again, this was a quite expensive endeavor,

665
00:35:52,689 --> 00:35:54,470
because you had to change a lot of the tuning,

666
00:35:54,490 --> 00:35:55,770
and you had to go through testing

667
00:35:56,211 --> 00:35:57,211
through the entire progression.

668
00:35:58,111 --> 00:36:01,013
Again, here, the winner was the shorter quest,

669
00:36:01,073 --> 00:36:04,354
but however, only marginally, because my suspicion here

670
00:36:04,414 --> 00:36:09,016
is that time it takes is actually just one thing,

671
00:36:09,036 --> 00:36:12,237
one thing that impacts the decision of whether players

672
00:36:12,337 --> 00:36:13,818
decide to stay with your game and retain.

673
00:36:18,160 --> 00:36:20,541
Another thing that we optimized was where features were locked.

674
00:36:20,701 --> 00:36:22,703
Again, we had a hypothesis here was

675
00:36:22,743 --> 00:36:25,745
that if we put feature x earlier in the game,

676
00:36:25,985 --> 00:36:28,727
maybe they will retain better because players now

677
00:36:28,767 --> 00:36:30,008
have access to more features.

678
00:36:31,029 --> 00:36:33,610
So this, again, fell into the, I think, again,

679
00:36:33,630 --> 00:36:35,852
we didn't quite realize that we still

680
00:36:35,872 --> 00:36:37,493
had a problem having too much content.

681
00:36:37,833 --> 00:36:41,136
So moving more content earlier, again, probably

682
00:36:41,596 --> 00:36:43,157
really didn't do anything in this case.

683
00:36:46,019 --> 00:36:48,601
So another thing worth noting is that be wary of the cost of

684
00:36:48,641 --> 00:36:49,963
testing every small change.

685
00:36:50,503 --> 00:36:53,486
Because every time, at least on Sims 3 Play, it wasn't super

686
00:36:53,506 --> 00:36:54,286
cheap to do everything.

687
00:36:54,326 --> 00:36:56,428
It was reasonably cheap, but it was still time.

688
00:36:56,448 --> 00:36:59,811
It was still time setting up the test, figuring out what we

689
00:36:59,831 --> 00:37:02,554
should test, as well as QA time.

690
00:37:10,121 --> 00:37:12,483
So when it came to validating learning.

691
00:37:13,825 --> 00:37:17,888
in the stage of maturity many years down the road,

692
00:37:18,728 --> 00:37:21,971
one of the things that we actually found was very hard

693
00:37:22,031 --> 00:37:24,252
was storing the lessons as memories.

694
00:37:26,234 --> 00:37:28,996
So most ideally, you imagine that we're spending years

695
00:37:29,076 --> 00:37:30,757
of doing something and all the mistakes

696
00:37:30,797 --> 00:37:31,738
and lessons that you've learned,

697
00:37:32,198 --> 00:37:34,279
we would like to build on the lessons of the past.

698
00:37:34,299 --> 00:37:37,562
However, this is a major challenge as we age

699
00:37:38,262 --> 00:37:40,023
because team members really, in reality,

700
00:37:40,104 --> 00:37:42,065
do not stay on the title forever.

701
00:37:43,183 --> 00:37:47,946
and that knowledge is normally, you know, disappears with them or at least different

702
00:37:47,966 --> 00:37:54,171
bits are left behind but not everything is left behind. This is hard because the team

703
00:37:54,631 --> 00:37:57,353
executes better if they understand why and how we got here.

704
00:37:59,361 --> 00:38:01,863
We don't have answers for this.

705
00:38:02,123 --> 00:38:03,665
We don't have great answers at least.

706
00:38:04,105 --> 00:38:07,328
We do have some things that we do with discipline,

707
00:38:07,748 --> 00:38:10,951
like we do an update telemetry review after every update,

708
00:38:10,991 --> 00:38:12,152
looking at our performance,

709
00:38:12,893 --> 00:38:15,615
looking at the things that we've tried and how they perform.

710
00:38:16,696 --> 00:38:18,237
We do some basic documentation,

711
00:38:18,257 --> 00:38:20,199
and we do things like that,

712
00:38:20,219 --> 00:38:21,560
just like as give talks,

713
00:38:21,640 --> 00:38:25,303
and hopefully there's some hand-me-down lessons

714
00:38:25,323 --> 00:38:26,965
that the new team members will learn.

715
00:38:29,500 --> 00:38:33,481
I really discovered that this was an issue when our team was trying to figure out

716
00:38:34,021 --> 00:38:35,462
what can we do with Quest?

717
00:38:35,642 --> 00:38:40,363
And this was seven years in, and I came to the realization that most people had no idea

718
00:38:40,383 --> 00:38:43,244
what had we tried before and what worked, what didn't.

719
00:38:44,244 --> 00:38:48,366
And in fact, a lot of the best practices that we had put in place previously had just been

720
00:38:48,446 --> 00:38:54,007
rolled back because of the different handovers that we had to keep doing as we changed designers,

721
00:38:54,087 --> 00:38:55,048
as we changed PMs.

722
00:38:56,090 --> 00:38:59,179
So what we did at least was the PM team put together

723
00:39:01,012 --> 00:39:03,613
all the different analysis that we had done on Quest,

724
00:39:03,653 --> 00:39:05,955
which was heaps, because we had tried anywhere

725
00:39:05,995 --> 00:39:09,097
between 10 to 15 to 20 different new things with Quest

726
00:39:09,157 --> 00:39:10,358
in the course of the years.

727
00:39:10,758 --> 00:39:12,679
And the good part was that they were all documented

728
00:39:12,720 --> 00:39:13,760
in telemetry reviews.

729
00:39:14,321 --> 00:39:18,023
So we created this massive Quest retrospective document,

730
00:39:18,864 --> 00:39:20,565
PowerPoint that we then presented to the team,

731
00:39:21,025 --> 00:39:22,346
explaining what worked, what didn't,

732
00:39:22,446 --> 00:39:25,068
what drove numbers, what did not,

733
00:39:25,188 --> 00:39:26,349
and where the opportunities were.

734
00:39:27,930 --> 00:39:29,091
And we presented it back to the team.

735
00:39:30,199 --> 00:39:33,040
And once we did that, we found that at least everyone

736
00:39:33,080 --> 00:39:36,662
started with close to the same amount of information, which

737
00:39:36,722 --> 00:39:40,524
then allowed us to then build on top of that in terms of

738
00:39:40,624 --> 00:39:41,485
what else can we do.

739
00:39:42,725 --> 00:39:43,786
But this is a lot of effort.

740
00:39:44,406 --> 00:39:47,768
And this is something that we really have to take into

741
00:39:47,788 --> 00:39:51,269
account as we go through hopefully what will be a very

742
00:39:51,309 --> 00:39:52,070
long life service.

743
00:39:55,107 --> 00:39:57,571
So lesson six, the validated learner.

744
00:39:58,292 --> 00:40:00,095
Every update is an opportunity to learn.

745
00:40:02,158 --> 00:40:03,540
Set up expectations ahead of time

746
00:40:03,580 --> 00:40:04,802
in order to improve your judgment.

747
00:40:06,665 --> 00:40:08,408
A-B testing is generally a really good way

748
00:40:08,448 --> 00:40:10,071
of measuring impact as well as uplift.

749
00:40:12,376 --> 00:40:15,680
And lastly, have a good plan to store lessons

750
00:40:16,340 --> 00:40:18,823
so that new team members can avoid making the same mistakes.

751
00:40:19,183 --> 00:40:21,085
But granted, sometimes people do have to make mistakes

752
00:40:21,125 --> 00:40:21,746
in order to learn.

753
00:40:21,806 --> 00:40:23,208
